<article class="content content--reading post">
  <a name="background"></a>
  <h1>Background</h1>

  <p>
    When I was leading Product Design at Grow Therapy, the company identified <strong>intersession engagement</strong> as one of its most important strategic priorities. We knew that the therapy experience couldn't just happen once a week in a one-hour session. If we wanted to deliver better care, support providers in getting paid for their time, and demonstrate outcomes strong enough to maintain and expand insurance contracts, we had to improve the quality of care that happened <em>between sessions</em>.
  </p>

  <p>
    At the time, however, our product surfaces were focused narrowly on logistics: helping clients schedule their first appointment and make sure they showed up prepared. I had strong conviction this was far too limited. A logistics-first app would never survive. In conversations with our CTO, VP of Product, and Group PMs, I pushed hard that <strong>intersession engagement had to become the core value proposition</strong> of our mobile app and broader care strategy. I wanted to anchor the client experience around pairing them with their provider in a way that extended beyond the session, and leadership eventually aligned with me on that direction.
  </p>

  <a name="team"></a>
  <h1>The Team</h1>

  <p>
    To make this real, I led design for a group that included <strong>Janice</strong>, a staff designer; <strong>Prabha</strong>, a staff PM; and later, <strong>Sophia</strong>, another designer who I pulled in for a specific strategy challenge. On the product side, <strong>Mayuri</strong> was my key partner and responsible for product side. My role as design leader became to set the ambition, coach the designers and product managers to think beyond narrow framing, and to secure executive alignment so the work could land as a core company initiative.
  </p>

  <a name="process"></a>
  <h1>The Process</h1>

  <h2>Recognizing Limited Ambition</h2>

  <p>
    The team's initial concept for <em>Session Topics</em> was tidy but small: twelve hours before a session, clients would get a prompt asking what they wanted to discuss. They could enter up to five short topics, which would then be shared with their provider.
  </p>

  <p>
    When I reviewed this, I recognized immediately that the <strong>problem space was not ambitious enough</strong>. It solved for the easy case — clients who already reflected and took notes — but not for the majority of clients who struggled most with reflection. It ignored the people who froze when prompted, who felt inhibited bringing up sensitive issues, or who simply didn't have the habit of reflecting at all.
  </p>

  <p>
    I aligned with a Group PM, and together we agreed that the scope had to expand. I pushed the team to reframe their questions: <em>How might we help people who don't know how to reflect? How might we support those who don't have the habit of reflection?</em> This reframing generated a much richer set of problem statements — ones that were both more ambitious and more customer-centered.
  </p>

  <h2>Driving Exploration</h2>

  <p>
    Once the team had reframed the problems, I wanted to break them out of incremental solutioning. I introduced a set of <strong>exploration frameworks</strong> to help them think bigger. I encouraged Janice and Prabha to study competitors for patterns in reflection and preparation, to use AI tools like ChatGPT and Subframe to generate divergent ideas (even pitting two AIs against each other), and to validate not just <em>whether</em> clients forgot topics, but <em>why reflection was difficult in the first place</em>.
  </p>

  <p>
    This push reframed the work and opened up a much more ambitious set of concepts. The team began exploring guided prompts pulled from past session transcripts to help clients "pick up where they left off." They tested visual reflection tools that allowed people to sketch or draw instead of writing. They built guided categories like <em>"Celebrate" → "a win at work"</em> or <em>"an improvement in my relationship."</em> They considered continuity prompts that nudged clients to build on prior reflections rather than starting from scratch.
  </p>

  <p>
    By forcing the team to experiment with new methods and approaches, I helped shift Session Topics from a narrow note-taking tool into a set of solutions that actually addressed the needs of clients who struggled most with reflection — the very people our company strategy demanded we serve better.
  </p>

  <h2>Championing Innovation (and Practicing Pragmatism)</h2>

  <p>
    One of the most ambitious directions I personally championed was <strong>audio-first reflection</strong>. From our recent acquisition of Summit, I had learned that their most engaged clients weren't the ones who chatted with their AI life coach — they were the ones who spoke to it. This supported my own hypothesis that reading and typing text while reflecting inhibited free-flow expression, whereas voice would unlock more authentic, natural reflection.
  </p>

  <p>
    I didn't leave this at gut instinct. I used <strong>ChatGPT's Deep Research feature</strong> to gather evidence from external sources on how conversational AI — particularly voice — could transform engagement. I then brought this evidence to our Group PM and our CTO, positioning audio-first not just as a feature idea, but as a <strong>strategic differentiator</strong> that could elevate Session Topics into something uniquely valuable.
  </p>

  <p>
    The CTO ultimately pushed back, arguing that testing audio outside of the mobile app wouldn't yield insights relevant enough to justify the investment. I disagreed, but I also knew when to adapt. I committed to punting the standalone experiment while ensuring audio-first reflection stayed in the <strong>mobile app roadmap</strong>.
  </p>

  <p>
    This moment highlighted two aspects of my leadership: my ability to <strong>champion innovation and scope expansion</strong>, pushing Session Topics beyond incremental improvements, and my ability to <strong>practice pragmatism and alignment</strong>, showing that even when I disagreed, I could commit to the organizational decision while preserving the long-term vision. It was a win: I broadened the scope of what Session Topics could mean strategically, introduced evidence-backed innovation, and kept the door open for future implementation.
  </p>

  <h2>Navigating Strategic Pivots</h2>

  <p>
    Two months into the work, Session Topics was folded into the <strong>mobile app roadmap</strong>, elevating it from a standalone feature into the foundation of the app's value proposition. This raised the stakes significantly.
  </p>

  <p>
    But as technical, scope, and staffing challenges mounted, intersession engagement was pulled back out, and Session Topics returned to being an independent product. My job then became guiding the team through these pivots, ensuring continuity of vision while adjusting execution strategy.
  </p>

  <h2>Guiding Execution</h2>

  <p>
    As we pivoted back to an independent launch, I worked closely with Janice, Prabha, and Mayuri through multiple design reviews — some with leadership, many with my direct approval. We iterated heavily, refining both the client experience and the provider workflow.
  </p>

  <p>
    Two interventions stand out:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>AI Summarization</strong>: Rather than limiting clients to short notes, I pushed for open reflections that we could then summarize with AI into discrete topics. Providers now received actionable summaries without being overwhelmed by raw text.</li>
    <li><strong>Dynamic Prompting Strategy</strong>: The team's original plan was to prompt clients exactly twenty-four hours before a session. I asked Janice to collaborate with Sophia to rethink the strategy around the real client journey: how long between selecting a therapist and their first session, how long between recurring sessions, and how to avoid fatigue by reducing prompts when a client had already reflected. This produced a smarter, more contextual prompting system that meaningfully improved engagement.</li>
  </ul>

  <a name="output"></a>
  <h1>The Output</h1>

  <p>
    The final version of Session Topics launched as a standalone experience. Clients could reflect openly, their responses were summarized by AI into topics, and providers received concise preparation material. It was simple, but it was ambitious: it turned raw client thoughts into structured, actionable conversation starters, and it did so in a way that aligned with both provider needs and payer outcomes.
  </p>
